ITEM 1 — "Increase the timeout threshold for peer delegation to prevent
timeouts on delegated general-task runs." ALREADY FIXED in the uncommitted
tree (confirm-not-a-bug for me to act on; the operator's edit is correct).
server/src/lib/peers.ts:224 (delegateToPeer) now reads
NEUROWORKS_PEER_DELEGATE_TIMEOUT_MS ?? 20*60_000 — bumped from 12 min to 20,
with a comment (lines 217-223) referencing exactly today's failure: "12 min
still timed out real delegated general-task runs (2026-07-20 journal: a
multi-source run hit the ceiling at 12min)." That matches the day's one
failure ("peer delegation timed out after Nmin", general-task template). One
loose end the operator should close while in there: the SECOND delegation path,
delegateToBestPeer (peers.ts:325), still defaults to 12*60_000 and was NOT
raised. Both read the same env var, so setting NEUROWORKS_PEER_DELEGATE_TIMEOUT_MS
overrides both — but the two hard-coded fallbacks now disagree (20 vs 12). If
the timed-out job routed through delegateToBestPeer rather than delegateToPeer,
the fix as staged wouldn't cover it. Worth aligning the two fallbacks (or
hoisting the 20-min default into one shared const) before committing.

ITEM 2 — "Investigate the schema or indexing for db.query to address the
31.5-second execution bottleneck." ALREADY FIXED in the uncommitted tree, and
the reflection's diagnosis was off. The 31.5s was NOT a DB schema/indexing
problem — the operator's edit in server/src/lib/data-sources.ts (lines 408-435)
identifies the real cause: question-mode db.query calls describeSource() on
EVERY question, which runs a full information_schema scan (a network round-trip;
a Neon serverless cold start alone adds several seconds) for a schema that
rarely changes. Fix staged: a per-source SCHEMA_CACHE with a 5-min TTL
(NEUROWORKS_DB_SCHEMA_CACHE_MS), keyed by source id, plus an
invalidateSchemaCache() export so editing a source's connection string doesn't
serve stale schema. Comment (line 415) cites the same "31–90s (2026-07-20
journal)" figure. This removes one of the two round-trips per question; the
other (LLM SQL generation) is inherent. No indexing change is warranted — the
bottleneck was app-level round-trips, not query planning. Nothing for me to add;
the staged fix is the right call.

ITEM 3 — "Rebalance task routing to utilize Aria and Piers more heavily, as
they only handled 2 tasks each." Confirmed real skew but NOT a bug — no code
change appropriate (same conclusion as the 2026-07-19 run's persona item). The
day's spread was Nova 6 / Neuro 5 / Aria 2 / Piers 2 over 18 tasks, which is a
mild content-driven distribution, not a routing pathology. Persona selection is
either explicit (operator/schedule names the persona) or auto-routed by
pickPersonaForTask (server/src/lib/persona-router.ts:344), which scores personas
by how well the TASK TEXT matches their patterns and only fires above a
confidence floor of 2 (persona-router.ts:342); genuine ties return null and
fall through to clawbot rather than dogpiling. It has no notion of "who's had
fewer tasks today" and deliberately shouldn't — forcing general work onto Aria
or Piers when the content matched Nova/Neuro would route tasks to the wrong
specialists and degrade output. If the operator genuinely wants routine work
spread across more personas, that's a schedule/template authoring choice (which
persona each scheduled task names), not something an unattended run should
decide by editing the router. No action taken.

